1 fewer than one-third provide health insurance or retirement benefits, highlighting the
2 ongoing challenges in ensuring a stable and supported early childhood workforce; and
3 WHEREAS, among child care providers who lost staff in 2024, nearly half reported
4 that departing employees left for jobs offering higher wages, with lower-paying providers
5 experiencing staff turnover at higher rates than those able to offer more competitive
6 compensation; and
7 WHEREAS, most child care providers report increased staffing costs or challenges,
8 including the ability to pay higher wages and hire experienced staff and experience high
9 turnover as new staff leave within six months of employment; and
10 WHEREAS, early childhood education is essential to a functioning economy and
11 early childhood educators are among the lowest-paid professionals in the education sector,
12 earning an average of $10.63 an hour in Louisiana despite the critical role they play during
13 a child's formative years in supporting the child's development and learning; and
14 WHEREAS, many early childhood educators earn wages so low that they qualify for
15 public assistance programs, highlighting the disconnect between the value of their work and
16 the compensation they receive; and
17 WHEREAS, studies have shown that inadequate pay contributes to higher turnover
18 rates among early childhood educators, disrupting the stability and quality of care that young
19 children need to thrive; and
20 WHEREAS, low wages often make it difficult to recruit and retain skilled, passionate
21 professionals in the early childhood education workforce, placing additional strain on child
22 care providers and families; and
23 WHEREAS, the lack of accessible, high quality early childhood education hinders
24 Louisiana's capacity to attract and keep young professionals, resulting in a loss of talent,
25 particularly in vital sectors like healthcare and education; and
26 WHEREAS, on Tuesday, May 12, 2026, child care providers, educators, families,
27 and community members across Louisiana are joining the National Day Without Child Care
28 to raise awareness about the urgent need for investment in early childhood education and to
29 advocate for a fully funded child care system that powers the economy and supports working
30 families; and
